commit 17a0e58a4a5e80c7fe85197550cf2f4a89e7e113
Author: Guilherme G. Piccoli <gpiccoli@igalia.com>

mm/memblock: Add reserve_mem debugfs info

This commit adds a new debugfs file "reserve_mem_param" to display the
successfully reserved memory regions passed via the "reserve_mem="
command-line parameter.

> --- a/mm/memblock.c
> +++ b/mm/memblock.c

[ ... ]

> +static int memblock_reserve_mem_show(struct seq_file *m, void *private)
> +{
> +	struct reserve_mem_table *map;
> +	char txtsz[16];
> +
> +	for (int i = 0; i < reserved_mem_count; i++) {
> +		map = &reserved_mem_table[i];
> +		if (!map->size)
> +			continue;

Can a concurrent call to reserve_mem_release_by_name() zero map->size while
this function is running?

Looking at reserve_mem_release_by_name(), it acquires reserve_mem_lock
before zeroing map->size:

mm/memblock.c:reserve_mem_release_by_name() {
    ...
    guard(mutex)(&reserve_mem_lock);
    map = reserve_mem_find_by_name_nolock(name);
    ...
    map->size = 0;
    ...
}

Because memblock_reserve_mem_show() does not hold reserve_mem_lock, a race
can occur between the !map->size check and the string_get_size() call below.

Additionally, on 32-bit architectures where phys_addr_t is 64-bit, this
could result in a torn read and cause a garbage value to be passed to
string_get_size().

Could we add guard(mutex)(&reserve_mem_lock) to protect this iteration?

> +
> +		memset(txtsz, 0, sizeof(txtsz));
> +		string_get_size(map->size, 1, STRING_UNITS_2, txtsz, sizeof(txtsz));
> +		seq_printf(m, "%s\t\t(%s)\n", map->name, txtsz);
> +	}
> +
> +	return 0;
> +}

